k, England":"Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"1279–1344":"1279–1344","1285–1340":"1285–1340","–Male":"Overleden","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England":"Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England":"Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1279–1344":"1279–1344","1285–1340":"1285–1340","–Male":"Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England":"Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England":"Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Averye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Aevery</i>, a Norman form of   Alfred  . Among the 17th-century Puritan settlers in New England, there was some confusion with   Averill  . Compare   Averett  .","Altered form of French Canadian <b>Hévey</b> (see   Hevey  ). Compare   Avey   3.","History: Christopher Avery emigrated from England to Salem, MA, in or before 1630. — William Avery (alias Averill) was one of the Puritan settlers who emigrated from England to Ipswich, MA, in or <i>c.</i> 1637. — Some of the American bearers of the surname <i>Avery</i> are descendants of Nicolas Hévé/Devé from France, who was in QC by 1672 (see   Hevey  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Avara","meanings":["Altered form of English   Avery  . See also   Avera  .","Italian (Sicily): from the feminine form of <b>Avaro</b>, a nickname from <i>avaro</i> ‘avaricious, mean, miserly’. This surname is very rare in Italy."]},{"name":"Averill","meanings":["English:","apparently from the name of the month (April), Middle English <i>averil</i>, Old French <i>avrill</i>, Latin <i>aprīlis</i>, perhaps with reference to freshness of temperament, or youth, or possibly to the changeable weather of the month.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Haverhill in Suffolk, with loss of initial <i>H-</i>. The placename derives from either Old English <i>hæfera</i> ‘oats’ or <i>hæfer</i> ‘he-goat’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Avery  ."]},{"name":"Avera","meanings":["Altered form of English   Avery  .","History: Richard Avery, from Fillongley, Warwickshire, is recorded in Surry, VA, in 1672. The surname was changed to <i>Avera</i> in the following generation and later also to <i>Avara</i>. A Jacob Avera is recorded in Johnson County, NC in 1764."]},{"name":"Avary","meanings":["English: variant of   Avery  ."]},{"name":"Every","meanings":["English (southwestern): variant of   Avery  ."]},{"name":"Alfred","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Arianne, Armand, Camille, Germine, Jacques, Jean-Claude, Magalie, Marcel, Michel, Patrice.","English, French, German, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and African (mainly Tanzania): from the Middle English personal name <i>Alfred</i>, <i>Elfred</i>, Old English <i>Ælfrǣd</i> ‘elf counsel’. This owed its popularity as a personal name in England to the fame of the West Saxon king Alfred the Great (849–899), who defeated the Danes, keeping them out of Wessex, and whose court was a great center of learning and culture."]},{"name":"Hevey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Nicolle.","French Canadian (<b>Hévey</b>): altered form of French <b>Hévé</b>, itself a variant or an altered form of <b>Devé</b>, an unflattering nickname from <i>desvé</i> ‘mad, insane’. The surname <i>Devé</i> originates from Normandy. Compare   Avery   2 and   Avey   3.","Irish (Meath): variant of   Heaphy  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":11,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":36,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":49,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":58,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Averye was born in 1279, in Buglawton, Cheshire, England. She married Philippus Broomyn in 1321, in Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1344, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1279–1344":"1279–1344","1285–1340":"1285–1340","–Male":"Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England":"Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England":"Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1279–1344":"1279–1344","1285–1340":"1285–1340","–Male":"Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England":"Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England":"Brome with Oakley, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1279–1344":"1279–1344","1285–1340":"1285–1340","–Male":"Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Buckland Monachorum, Devon, England":"Buckland Monachorum, Devon, Angleterre","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royau